---
# Active tracker. Options: linear | github | jira | auto
# - `auto` runs a detection cascade (MCP probe → CLI probe → branch hint → prompt).
# - Setting this explicitly skips the cascade.
tracker: auto

# Base URL for ticket links. Skills append the ticket ID (or /N for GitHub).
# Examples:
#   Linear:  https://linear.app/yourteam/issue
#   JIRA:    https://your-org.atlassian.net/browse
#   GitHub:  https://github.com/owner/repo/issues
ticket_url_base: https://linear.app/yourteam/issue

# Regex for matching ticket IDs in branch names and commit messages.
# Default works for Linear and JIRA. For GitHub-only projects you can leave this
# as-is — the tracker resolution also recognizes plain integers.
ticket_id_regex: "[A-Z][A-Z0-9]+-[0-9]+"

# Only used when tracker is `github` (or auto-detected to github).
# If omitted, /ccmagic:work-ticket runs `gh repo view --json nameWithOwner` to detect.
# github_repo: owner/repo

# If true, /ccmagic:finish-ticket defaults to the QA path (move ticket to a QA
# state and assign a reviewer). If false or absent, the default disposition is Done
# and QA must be requested explicitly via --qa.
default_qa_workflow: false

# Optional: label applied on GitHub Issues when the QA path is selected
# (GitHub has no built-in QA state). Ignored for Linear/JIRA.
# qa_label: needs-qa

# --- Autonomous mode (used by /ccmagic:auto-ticket and the autonomous paths of
#     work-ticket / review-ticket / pr-feedback / finish-ticket / push) ---

# Default mode when a skill is invoked WITHOUT --autonomous and WITHOUT an
# orchestrator grounding block. When true, those skills run their autonomous
# (non-interactive) path by default. /ccmagic:auto-ticket always runs
# autonomously regardless of this value.
autonomous: false

# Tracker state a "needs a human" ticket is parked in during an autonomous run
# (e.g. "Blocked", "Needs Human"). If this state/transition doesn't exist in your
# tracker, the run falls back to needs_human_label below and leaves state unchanged.
# needs_human_state: Blocked

# Fallback label applied when a ticket is parked and needs_human_state doesn't
# exist — and always on GitHub Issues, which have no custom states.
needs_human_label: needs-human

# Cap on /ccmagic:pr-feedback loop iterations during an autonomous run before the
# ticket is parked for a human.
max_feedback_passes: 3
---

# ccmagic project settings

Copy this file to **`.claude/ccmagic.local.md`** in your project root and edit the frontmatter to match your team's setup. The tracker-aware ccmagic skills (`work-ticket`, `finish-ticket`, `review-ticket`, and the autonomous driver `auto-ticket`) read this file if present; otherwise they auto-detect.

## Recognized keys

| Key | Purpose | Default if absent |
|-----|---------|-------------------|
| `tracker` | Active tracker — `linear`, `github`, `jira`, or `auto`. | `auto` |
| `ticket_url_base` | Base URL for ticket links. | placeholder |
| `ticket_id_regex` | Branch/commit detection regex. | `[A-Z][A-Z0-9]+-[0-9]+` |
| `github_repo` | `owner/repo` for GitHub issues. | auto-detected via `gh repo view` |
| `default_qa_workflow` | If `true`, `finish-ticket` defaults to the QA path. | `false` |
| `qa_label` | Label applied to GitHub issues on the QA path. | none (skill asks first time) |
| `autonomous` | Default mode when no `--autonomous` flag and no orchestrator grounding block is passed. | `false` |
| `needs_human_state` | Tracker state a parked ("needs a human") ticket is moved to during an autonomous run. | none (falls back to `needs_human_label`) |
| `needs_human_label` | Fallback label applied when `needs_human_state` doesn't exist (and always on GitHub). | `needs-human` |
| `max_feedback_passes` | Cap on the `pr-feedback` loop in an autonomous run before parking. | `3` |

## How the detection cascade works

When `tracker: auto` (or unset), the tracker-aware skills run this cascade:

1. **Arg/branch shape hint** — integer-only ticket ID → GitHub; `[A-Z]+-[0-9]+` → Linear or JIRA.
2. **MCP probe** — check for `mcp__*Linear*__get_issue` (Linear) and `mcp__*atlassian*__*` (JIRA).
3. **CLI probe** — `command -v gh && gh repo view` (GitHub).
4. **Branch hint** — match the current branch against `ticket_url_base` if ambiguous.
5. **Ask once** — if multiple match or none match, prompt the user and offer to save the choice here.

## Autonomous mode

The tracker-lifecycle skills (`work-ticket`, `review-ticket`, `pr-feedback`, `finish-ticket`, `push`) have an **opt-in, additive** autonomous path, and `/ccmagic:auto-ticket` drives the whole cycle unattended. Interactive behavior is never changed — autonomous only kicks in when a signal is present.

A skill enters autonomous mode when the first present signal (in priority order) is truthy:

1. `--autonomous` in the skill's arguments.
2. An `autonomous: true` line in the grounding block that `/ccmagic:auto-ticket` prepends when it invokes a sub-skill.
3. `autonomous: true` here in `.claude/ccmagic.local.md`.

The core safety property is **not** "avoid merging" — for solo-dev projects, auto-merge with no human in the loop is fine. It's that when work is genuinely uncertain or needs a human decision, the run **parks** the ticket instead of guessing or stalling: it does not merge, moves the ticket to `needs_human_state` (or applies `needs_human_label` if that state doesn't exist), posts a comment explaining exactly what it's waiting on, and exits cleanly. Every autonomous run ends either **merged** or **parked-needs-human** — never hung.

See the plugin's `README.md` (*Autonomous mode*) for the full flow and the `/ccmagic:auto-ticket` skill for the orchestration contract.

## Optional markdown body

Anything below the frontmatter is free-form context that skills may read for project-specific guidance (e.g. naming conventions for branches, required reviewers, deploy notes). Keep it short — it's loaded into context whenever a ccmagic skill reads this file.

## How skills read this

Skills check for `.claude/ccmagic.local.md` relative to the git repo root (`git rev-parse --show-toplevel`). If the file exists, parse the YAML frontmatter and use the values. If it doesn't exist, run the auto-detection cascade.
